{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab this script should ultimately help you to get rid of any MIDI Editor zooming issues. Assign it to the Enter key and it will open the MIDI Editor and zoom to 5 measures (default). You can adjust the measures in the user area.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab this code is based to 99% on Julian's code, I only added the open MIDI editor command and cleaned up unnecessary parts.\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab this script mimics the behaviour of Nuendo's Edit Mode. You select an item, execute the script and move/nudge the item with the mouse. As result, the edit cursor will snap to the start of the item and follow your mouse movement.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab the script is executed as an endless loop, so you have to terminate it, when you are done. Best is, to assign it as a shortcut and terminate it when pressing the shortcut again.\sa180\par}
}
